name: N-boc-L-proline
Reason: To predict the melting point of N-boc-L-proline, we consider the effects of its functional groups on the base structure, proline. The basic unit proline has a melting point around 220 degrees Celsius. The Boc group (tert-butoxycarbonyl), which protects the amino group, introduces steric bulk and enhances the molecular weight, but it also disrupts the ability for the molecule to pack efficiently in a solid state, typically reducing the melting point; this can have a -60 to -100 degrees Celsius effect. The carboxylic acid group is maintained as in proline, contributing to the potential for hydrogen bonding, but since the Boc group is already considered, we won't count its effect again. Therefore, we subtract the Boc group effect from the basic proline melting point.
Prediction: 160 to 120 (220 - 60 to 220 - 100 for the Boc group)
